<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1879-12-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1879-12-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="575" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d575">
                    <head>No. 575.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Evarts</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Lowell</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1879-12-10"><hi rend="italic">December</hi> 10,
                            1879</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 185.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your No.
                        216, regarding the proposed law for the abolition of slavery in Cuba; and,
                        in reply, to express to you the satisfaction which is felt by the government
                        at the intelligence on this subject, which your communication conveys; not
                        only in the circumstance of the proposed abolition by Spain, but because
                        this measure must be looked upon as a great step to complete and universal
                        emancipation.</p>
                    <p>I am, sir, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>WM. M. EVARTS.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>